summaries.title: Summary 312.1
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 312.2
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Summary 312.3
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 1]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 2]
Presented a project on sustainable energy systems at an undergraduate research showcase. [Timeline 4]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge.

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 4]

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 3]
Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 3]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 3]
When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 2]
If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 1]
When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 4]
